headline.main: Atlanta Symphony Orchestra Agrees to a New Labor Deal
headline.print_headline: Atlanta Symphony Orchestra Agrees to a New Labor Deal

docs.abstract: Atlanta Symphony Orchestra says it will end its two-month lockout after reaching deal that will give its musicians small raises but require them to pay more for their health insurance, while also allowing the orchestra to leave positions vacant longer.
docs.snippet: The agreement, which resolves a two-month lockout, will give the musicians small raises but require them to pay higher health insurance rates.

docs.lead_paragraph: Patients face a tortuous process to obtain their own information.
docs.abstract: News analysis; many patients in the United States face tortuous process to obtain their own medical records; many hospitals and doctors have created series of hurdles that must be cleared before patients can get their information, many of which are based on trying to keep patient as a customer.

docs.abstract: First column by Prof Abraham Verghese reflects on fears doctors have when treating patients suffering from infectious diseases, such as Ebola, and how these anxieties conflict with doctors' impulse to help victims; says strategy that punishes doctors who put themselves at risk, rather than rewarding them, is flawed.
